# DOCUMENTATION RULES
## CORE PHILOSOPHY
Documentation is code. It must be concise, synchronously updated, and focused on context over mechanics.

## ARCHITECTURE & DECISIONS
- Maintain an Architectural Decision Records (ADR) log for all significant technical choices. Include Context, Decision, and Consequences.
- Provide a high-level system architecture diagram or text equivalent in the root documentation.

## INLINE COMMENTS
- Document the "Why", not the "What". Code explains how it works; comments explain why it was written that way.
- Flag technical debt explicitly with standardized tags (e.g., `TODO:`, `FIXME:`, `HACK:`).
- Add rich type-hinting/docstrings to all public APIs detailing inputs, outputs, side-effects, and thrown errors.

## REPOSITORY README
- The README must contain: 
  1. Purpose of the system.
  2. Prerequisites (exact tooling versions).
  3. One-command setup instructions.
  4. Run/Test instructions.